// LifeOS AI — Prisma schema.
// Lives at the repo root per docs/07-folder-structure.md so it's shared, not owned by one app.
// Models are added incrementally, one feature milestone at a time (see docs/09-roadmap.md).
// Milestone 2 (Authentication) adds User/RefreshToken from docs/06-database-design.md.
// UserSettings is part of the same doc's "Identity & access" block but isn't needed by any
// Milestone 2 endpoint, so it's deferred to the milestone that actually reads/writes it rather
// than being created unused.
// Milestone 4 (Task Management) adds Task, using the simplified field set given for that
// milestone rather than the full docs/06-database-design.md shape — see the comment on Task.
// Milestone 5 (Routine Engine) adds Routine/RoutineStep — a new module not named in
// docs/06-database-design.md (the closest existing concept is ScheduleTemplate's JSON blob);
// see the comment on Routine for why it's modeled as first-class relational tables instead.
// Milestone 6 (Habit Tracker) adds Habit/HabitLog, using that milestone's simplified field set
// (targetFrequency/targetCount instead of docs/06-database-design.md's isQuantifiable/unit, and
// completedCount/notes on HabitLog instead of completed/value) — see the comment on Habit.
// Milestone 7 (Daily Planner) adds PlannerDay/PlannerBlock — a new concept not named in
// docs/06-database-design.md (the closest existing concept is ScheduleBlock); see the comment on
// PlannerDay for why it's split into a day container + blocks rather than reusing ScheduleBlock.
// Milestone 8 (Streak Engine & Gamification Foundation) adds Achievement/UserAchievement/
// FreezeDay. Streak values themselves (current/longest streak, consistency %, XP) are NOT
// modeled as columns anywhere, per that milestone's brief — HabitLog (plus Task/PlannerBlock for
// XP) remains the sole source of truth and every number is recomputed on read by
// modules/streaks, the same "derived, not stored" principle Habit/Routine already apply to their
// own completion percentages. See the comment on Achievement for the full rationale.
// Milestone 9 (Goals & Goal Tracking) adds Goal/GoalMilestone, plus an optional `goalId` on
// Task/Habit/Routine/PlannerBlock so any of those can opt into contributing to a Goal's progress.
// Unlike Streaks, Goal.currentValue *is* a real stored column (the milestone brief lists it
// explicitly, and CUSTOM goals need somewhere for a manual value to live) — see the comment on
// Goal for the read/recompute contract that keeps it from drifting out of sync with the source
// data it's derived from for the four automatic target types.
// Milestone 10 (Journal, Reflection & Life Timeline) adds JournalEntry/JournalPrompt/
// JournalAttachment. JournalEntry is deliberately a single wide table covering all three
// JournalType variants (MORNING/EVENING/FREEFORM) with nullable type-specific columns, rather than
// per-type tables — see the comment on JournalEntry for why. It carries the same optional `goalId`
// pattern Task/Habit/Routine/PlannerBlock already established (Milestone 9) plus a new, symmetric
// optional `plannerDayId`, so an entry can reference the day it reflects on. JournalService also
// exports its service (like Tasks/Routines/Habits/Planner already do) purely so a future AI Coach
// module can import JournalModule and read a user's journal history as coaching context — no AI
// code is added in this milestone, only the same "export for reuse" seam every prior
// service-composing milestone has used.
// Milestone 11 (Calendar & External Integrations) adds Calendar/CalendarEvent/CalendarSync.
// Calendar is a user-owned container (LOCAL by default, or a placeholder row for a future
// GOOGLE/MICROSOFT/APPLE/ICAL connection — see the comment on Calendar for why "connecting" a
// provider is still just a local row today). CalendarEvent is the scheduling layer's actual
// content — optionally cross-linked to a PlannerBlock/Task/Goal/JournalEntry via nullable
// `onDelete: SetNull` FKs, the same "optional, one-directional, ownership-checked via raw Prisma
// existence check" pattern Task/Habit/Routine/PlannerBlock already established for `goalId` and
// JournalEntry established for `goalId`/`plannerDayId` — see the comment on CalendarEvent for the
// full rationale and why deleting a linked Task/Goal/PlannerBlock/JournalEntry only detaches the
// event (SetNull) rather than deleting the user's calendar history. CalendarSync is an
// append-only per-sync-attempt log, not a single "last known state" row, so a calendar's sync
// history is itself inspectable — see the comment on CalendarSync.
// Milestone 12 (Notification Engine) adds Notification/NotificationPreference/NotificationQueue.
// This is the first milestone to introduce EventEmitter2 as a real, wired dependency (see
// docs/05-architecture.md's Milestone 12 note) — Notification rows are created by
// modules/notifications' NotificationSchedulerService reacting to domain events (TaskCompleted,
// HabitCompleted, PlannerBlockCompleted, GoalCompleted, JournalCreated, AchievementUnlocked)
// emitted by small, additive changes to TasksService/HabitsService/PlannerService/GoalsService/
// JournalService/AchievementsService, not by those modules calling NotificationsService directly.
// NotificationPreference is a per-user (1:1) settings row, auto-created with defaults on first
// access — the same "find-or-create on first read" convention PlannerDay/HabitLog already use for
// their own per-user rows. NotificationQueue is a 1:1 delivery-attempt ledger for one Notification
// (attempts/nextAttempt/lastError/status), the seam a future BullMQ worker process would drain —
// see the comment on NotificationQueue for why, unlike CalendarSync's append-only log, this one
// row is mutated in place across retries.
// Milestone 13 (AI Coach & Personal Insights) adds AiInsight/AiConversation/AiMessage. This is a
// strictly read-only analysis layer — modules/ai composes Tasks/Habits/Planner/Streaks/Goals/
// Journal/Notifications' own exported, read-only methods (never their write paths, and never
// GoalsService.getProgress/StreaksService.getStatistics specifically, since both have a persisting
// side effect — see the comment on AiInsight) to compute metrics, then an AiProvider (MockAiProvider
// today; OpenAiProvider/AnthropicProvider/GoogleAiProvider are unimplemented placeholders, the same
// "real interface, one real adapter, honest NOT_IMPLEMENTED others" shape Calendar/Notifications
// already established) turns those metrics into human-readable insight text. AiInsight rows are
// this analysis's durable output; AiConversation/AiMessage store the AI Chat feature's turn-by-turn
// history. `StreaksModule`/`GoalsModule` each gained a one-line additive `exports: [...Service]` (no
// existing behavior changed) so AiAnalysisService can reuse them the same "reuse services" way every
// prior fan-in module (Planner/Streaks/Goals) already does — see docs/05-architecture.md's
// Milestone 13 note for the full rationale.

generator client {
  provider = "prisma-client-js"
  output   = "../apps/backend/generated/prisma"
}

datasource db {
  provider = "postgresql"
  url      = env("DATABASE_URL")
}

// Matches docs/06-database-design.md's User.role enum exactly (STANDARD/PREMIUM/ADMIN) even
// though Milestone 2's RBAC only branches on ADMIN vs. everyone else — PREMIUM becomes
// meaningful once the Subscriptions module exists. Keeping the full enum now avoids a breaking
// migration later just to add a value.
enum Role {
  STANDARD
  PREMIUM
  ADMIN
}

model User {
  id              String    @id @default(uuid())
  email           String    @unique
  // Nullable because a future Google OAuth-only user (docs/06-database-design.md) has no
  // local password. Not implemented in Milestone 2, but the schema already accommodates it.
  passwordHash    String?
  googleId        String?   @unique
  name            String
  avatarUrl       String?
  role            Role      @default(STANDARD)
  timezone        String    @default("UTC")
  locale          String    @default("en")
  emailVerifiedAt DateTime?
  isActive        Boolean   @default(true)
  createdAt       DateTime  @default(now())
  updatedAt       DateTime  @updatedAt
  deletedAt       DateTime?

  refreshTokens          RefreshToken[]
  tasks                  Task[]
  routines               Routine[]
  habits                 Habit[]
  plannerDays            PlannerDay[]
  userAchievements       UserAchievement[]
  freezeDays             FreezeDay[]
  goals                  Goal[]
  journalEntries         JournalEntry[]
  calendars              Calendar[]
  notifications          Notification[]
  notificationPreference NotificationPreference?
  aiInsights             AiInsight[]
  aiConversations        AiConversation[]

  @@map("users")
}

model RefreshToken {
  id     String @id @default(uuid())
  userId String
  user   User   @relation(fields: [userId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)

  // bcrypt hash of the token's random secret half — never the raw token. See
  // AuthService's selector/verifier scheme for why `id` doubles as the lookup key.
  tokenHash  String
  deviceInfo String?
  expiresAt  DateTime
  revokedAt  DateTime?
  createdAt  DateTime  @default(now())

  @@index([userId])
  @@map("refresh_tokens")
}

// Priority/status names and the field list here follow Milestone 4's brief exactly rather than
// docs/06-database-design.md's fuller Task shape (which also has parentTaskId/category/
// recurrenceRule and a many-to-many Tag entity). Those are deferred — not needed by any
// Milestone 4 endpoint — rather than built unused; `tags` is a flat string array for now instead
// of a relational Tag/TaskTag join.
enum TaskPriority {
  LOW
  MEDIUM
  HIGH
  CRITICAL
}

enum TaskStatus {
  TODO
  IN_PROGRESS
  COMPLETED
  CANCELLED
}

model Task {
  id     String @id @default(uuid())
  userId String
  user   User   @relation(fields: [userId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)

  title            String
  description      String?
  priority         TaskPriority @default(MEDIUM)
  status           TaskStatus   @default(TODO)
  dueDate          DateTime?
  estimatedMinutes Int?
  completedAt      DateTime?
  tags             String[]     @default([])

  // Milestone 9: optional link to a Goal this task contributes to. `onDelete: SetNull` — deleting
  // a Goal detaches its tasks rather than deleting them; a Task's own lifecycle never depends on
  // its Goal's. See the comment on Goal for how TASK_COUNT progress is computed from this.
  goalId String?
  goal   Goal?   @relation(fields: [goalId], references: [id], onDelete: SetNull)

  createdAt DateTime  @default(now())
  updatedAt DateTime  @updatedAt
  // Soft delete, per docs/06-database-design.md's design principles (Task is named there
  // explicitly) — DELETE /tasks/:id sets this instead of removing the row, so it stays
  // recoverable and consistent with how the rest of the schema treats user-generated content.
  deletedAt DateTime?

  // Milestone 11: CalendarEvents that optionally reference this task — see the comment on
  // CalendarEvent. Deleting a Task never deletes its linked CalendarEvent(s) (onDelete: SetNull
  // on the other side), so calendar history survives its source Task being removed.
  calendarEvents CalendarEvent[]

  @@index([userId, status])
  @@index([userId, dueDate])
  @@index([goalId])
  @@map("tasks")
}

// A Routine is a repeatable *daily template* (e.g. "Morning Routine"), not tied to a specific
// calendar date — that's why RoutineStep.startTime is a plain "HH:mm" string rather than a
// DateTime: there is no date for it to belong to. No `type` field (Morning/Evening/Custom) is
// modeled — those are just names/icons a user picks, not a fixed enum in the brief. No
// completion-tracking field/table is added either: neither Routine nor RoutineStep's given field
// list includes one, so the dashboard's "Routine completion %" is computed as time-elapsed
// progress through today's steps (frontend-only, from startTime), not persisted per-day
// completion state — see docs/06-database-design.md's note on Routine for the full rationale.
model Routine {
  id     String @id @default(uuid())
  userId String
  user   User   @relation(fields: [userId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)

  name        String
  icon        String
  color       String
  description String?
  isActive    Boolean @default(true)

  // Milestone 9: optional link to a Goal this routine contributes to. ROUTINE_COMPLETION progress
  // walks from here to this routine's steps to the completed PlannerBlocks that reference them —
  // see the comment on Goal.
  goalId String?
  goal   Goal?   @relation(fields: [goalId], references: [id], onDelete: SetNull)

  createdAt DateTime @default(now())
  updatedAt DateTime @updatedAt

  steps RoutineStep[]

  @@index([userId, isActive])
  @@index([goalId])
  @@map("routines")
}

model RoutineStep {
  id        String  @id @default(uuid())
  routineId String
  routine   Routine @relation(fields: [routineId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)

  title                 String
  // "HH:mm", 24-hour, local time-of-day — see the comment on Routine for why not DateTime.
  startTime             String
  durationMinutes       Int
  order                 Int
  reminderMinutesBefore Int?
  isRequired            Boolean @default(true)

  @@index([routineId, order])
  @@map("routine_steps")
}

// Milestone 6's field list replaces docs/06-database-design.md's Habit shape
// (targetFrequency enum(DAILY, WEEKLY, CUSTOM) + isQuantifiable/unit) with a simpler
// targetFrequency(DAILY/WEEKLY/MONTHLY) + targetCount pair — "do this targetCount times per
// period" covers both boolean habits (targetCount: 1) and quantifiable ones (e.g. targetCount: 8
// for "8 glasses of water") without a separate isQuantifiable/unit pair. `reminderTime` reuses
// RoutineStep's "HH:mm" string convention (time-of-day with no calendar date attached).
// No completion/streak columns live here: "today's completion status" and the various
// completion percentages the endpoints return are computed from HabitLog on every read — the
// same "computed, not persisted" choice made for Routine's completion %, and consistent with
// docs/06-database-design.md's own principle that Streak is derived state rolled up from a log,
// not a source of truth in its own right. Actual streak *tracking* is Milestone 7's Streak
// Engine — this milestone deliberately computes only same-period/same-day progress.
enum HabitFrequency {
  DAILY
  WEEKLY
  MONTHLY
}

model Habit {
  id     String @id @default(uuid())
  userId String
  user   User   @relation(fields: [userId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)

  name            String
  description     String?
  icon            String
  color           String
  targetFrequency HabitFrequency @default(DAILY)
  targetCount     Int            @default(1)
  category        String?
  // "HH:mm", 24-hour, local time-of-day — see the comment above for why not DateTime.
  reminderTime    String?
  isActive        Boolean        @default(true)

  // Milestone 9: optional link to a Goal this habit contributes to. HABIT_COMPLETION progress
  // counts this habit's HabitLog rows — see the comment on Goal.
  goalId String?
  goal   Goal?   @relation(fields: [goalId], references: [id], onDelete: SetNull)

  createdAt DateTime  @default(now())
  updatedAt DateTime  @updatedAt
  // Soft delete, per docs/06-database-design.md's design principles — Habit is named there
  // explicitly, same as Task.
  deletedAt DateTime?

  logs HabitLog[]

  // Backs "validate duplicate habit names per user": a habit named the same as one the user
  // already has is rejected at the service layer with a friendly 409 (see HabitsService), and
  // this constraint is the last-resort backstop against a race between two concurrent creates.
  @@unique([userId, name])
  @@index([userId, isActive])
  @@index([goalId])
  @@map("habits")
}

model HabitLog {
  id      String @id @default(uuid())
  habitId String
  habit   Habit  @relation(fields: [habitId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)

  // Date-only (no time-of-day) — a habit is logged at most once per calendar day, per the unique
  // constraint below, regardless of what time that day the user actually did it.
  date           DateTime @db.Date
  completedCount Int      @default(1)
  notes          String?

  createdAt DateTime @default(now())

  // Backs "prevent multiple logs for the same habit/date" at the database level.
  @@unique([habitId, date])
  @@index([habitId, date])
  @@map("habit_logs")
}

// A PlannerDay is a thin per-(user, date) container; PlannerBlock rows carry the actual
// schedule. Split into two models — rather than one flat table, or reusing
// docs/06-database-design.md's ScheduleBlock — because the Planner's own fields (`notes`) belong
// to the *day*, not any one block, and every planner endpoint operates "for this user, on this
// date" first and block-by-block second. `ScheduleBlock` was never implemented (Planner is its
// first real implementation), so there's no migration/back-compat concern in choosing this shape
// over that one.
model PlannerDay {
  id     String @id @default(uuid())
  userId String
  user   User   @relation(fields: [userId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)

  // Date-only, like HabitLog.date — a planner day has no time-of-day of its own.
  date  DateTime @db.Date
  notes String?

  createdAt DateTime @default(now())
  updatedAt DateTime @updatedAt

  blocks         PlannerBlock[]
  // Milestone 10: entries that reflect on this specific day (e.g. an Evening Journal's Planner
  // Reflection). Optional and one-directional — PlannerDay has no reciprocal knowledge of, or
  // dependency on, Journal; see the comment on JournalEntry.
  journalEntries JournalEntry[]

  // A user has at most one PlannerDay per date — GET /planner/today and GET /planner/:date
  // find-or-create against this constraint rather than requiring a separate provisioning step.
  @@unique([userId, date])
  @@index([userId, date])
  @@map("planner_days")
}

// TASK/ROUTINE/HABIT blocks are the ones POST /planner/generate creates and may replace on
// regeneration; FOCUS/BREAK/CUSTOM are always user-authored and generation never touches them.
// See the comment on PlannerService.generate for the full regeneration contract.
enum PlannerBlockType {
  TASK
  ROUTINE
  HABIT
  FOCUS
  BREAK
  CUSTOM
}

model PlannerBlock {
  id           String     @id @default(uuid())
  plannerDayId String
  plannerDay   PlannerDay @relation(fields: [plannerDayId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)

  type        PlannerBlockType
  // Polymorphic-by-reference (Task.id / RoutineStep.id / Habit.id), the same pattern
  // docs/06-database-design.md's ScheduleBlock uses — no FK constraint, since the referenced
  // table depends on `type`. Null for FOCUS/BREAK/CUSTOM, which have no backing source record.
  // Completing or deleting a PlannerBlock never writes back to the referenced Task/Habit — see
  // the comment on PlannerService.complete for why that's a deliberate business rule, not an
  // oversight.
  referenceId String?
  title       String
  description String?
  startTime   DateTime
  endTime     DateTime
  // Derived from (endTime - startTime) and recomputed by PlannerService on every create/update
  // rather than trusted from the client — see docs/05-architecture.md's database rules ("derived
  // values should be calculated whenever practical"). Stored (not computed on read) because it's
  // the field the milestone brief names explicitly and because every list view needs it without
  // re-deriving per row.
  duration    Int
  color       String?
  completed   Boolean          @default(false)
  // Manual sort key for same/overlapping-time blocks and drag-reorder — independent of
  // chronological startTime ordering, same role RoutineStep.order plays for routines.
  order       Int

  // Milestone 9: optional link to a Goal this block directly contributes to — independent of
  // `referenceId`/`type`. FOCUS_TIME progress sums `duration` across a goal's completed blocks
  // regardless of type, per the "Planner: completed planner blocks contribute automatically"
  // business rule — see the comment on Goal.
  goalId String?
  goal   Goal?   @relation(fields: [goalId], references: [id], onDelete: SetNull)

  createdAt DateTime @default(now())
  updatedAt DateTime @updatedAt

  // Milestone 11: CalendarEvents that optionally reference this block — see the comment on
  // CalendarEvent. "Planner blocks may create calendar events" (the milestone's own business
  // rule) means POST /calendar/events accepts an optional `plannerBlockId`, not that PlannerBlock
  // itself gains any Calendar awareness — PlannerService is untouched by this milestone.
  calendarEvents CalendarEvent[]

  @@index([plannerDayId, order])
  @@index([plannerDayId, startTime])
  @@index([goalId])
  @@map("planner_blocks")
}

// Catalog of unlockable achievements — data-driven by design (per the milestone brief's "avoid
// hardcoding logic inside controllers"): each row's `code` is looked up against a single
// TypeScript definitions array (modules/streaks/utils/achievement-definitions.ts) that owns the
// actual unlock condition and xpReward, so adding/tuning an achievement never requires touching
// AchievementsController/StreaksController. Rows are upserted from that array at boot
// (AchievementsService.onModuleInit) rather than via a separate `prisma db seed` step — one
// source of truth (the TS array) instead of two (a seed script + this table) that could drift.
model Achievement {
  id          String   @id @default(uuid())
  code        String   @unique
  title       String
  description String
  icon        String
  xpReward    Int
  createdAt   DateTime @default(now())

  unlocks UserAchievement[]

  @@map("achievements")
}

// The durable record of *when* a user actually earned an achievement — everything else about
// streaks/consistency/XP is recomputed on every read (see the comment above), but an unlock
// instant is a genuine fact no other table could derive, so it's the one place this milestone
// persists state. Achievements are evaluated (and unlocked, if newly earned) as a side effect of
// reading GET /streaks/statistics, /streaks, or /achievements* — see AchievementsService's class
// doc for why this is a pull/read-time evaluation rather than a live NestJS domain-event
// subscription.
model UserAchievement {
  id            String      @id @default(uuid())
  userId        String
  user          User        @relation(fields: [userId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)
  achievementId String
  achievement   Achievement @relation(fields: [achievementId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)
  unlockedAt    DateTime    @default(now())

  @@unique([userId, achievementId])
  @@index([userId])
  @@map("user_achievements")
}

// One row per calendar date a user has spent a streak-freeze on — the "recovery streak" mechanic
// docs/03-assumptions.md (#2) and docs/04-improvements.md (#2) flagged as undefined, resolved
// here as a small monthly quota (FreezeDaysService.FREEZE_DAYS_PER_MONTH) of forgivable missed
// days, Duolingo-style. `consumed` defaults to true because this milestone has no "reserve a
// freeze for later" concept — the only codepath that creates a row (POST /freeze-days/use) does
// so at the moment of use — but is still a real, queryable column (not merely implied by the
// row's existence) so a future "auto-apply my remaining freezes to any day I miss" job could mark
// a pre-granted freeze un-consumed until it's actually needed, without a schema change.
model FreezeDay {
  id        String   @id @default(uuid())
  userId    String
  user      User     @relation(fields: [userId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)
  // Date-only, like HabitLog.date/PlannerDay.date — the calendar date being protected, not the
  // instant the freeze was spent (that's createdAt).
  date      DateTime @db.Date
  consumed  Boolean  @default(true)
  createdAt DateTime @default(now())

  // A user can only spend one freeze per calendar date.
  @@unique([userId, date])
  @@index([userId, date])
  @@map("freeze_days")
}

enum GoalStatus {
  NOT_STARTED
  ACTIVE
  PAUSED
  COMPLETED
  CANCELLED
}

enum GoalPriority {
  LOW
  MEDIUM
  HIGH
  CRITICAL
}

// What GET /goals/:id/progress recomputes `currentValue` from. Each automatic type corresponds
// 1:1 to one of the milestone brief's four "contribute automatically" sources (Tasks/Habits/
// Routine/Planner) via that source's own optional `goalId` link; CUSTOM has no automatic source
// at all — `currentValue` only ever changes for a CUSTOM goal via PATCH /goals/:id.
enum GoalTargetType {
  TASK_COUNT
  HABIT_COMPLETION
  ROUTINE_COMPLETION
  FOCUS_TIME
  CUSTOM
}

// The highest-level entity in LifeOS: Task/Habit/Routine/PlannerBlock can each optionally point
// back at a Goal via their own `goalId` (see those models' comments), and a Goal's `currentValue`
// is what GoalsService.getProgress recomputes from whichever of those four relations matches its
// own `targetType` — TASK_COUNT counts this goal's completed Tasks, HABIT_COMPLETION counts
// HabitLog rows for this goal's Habits, ROUTINE_COMPLETION counts completed ROUTINE-type
// PlannerBlocks whose referenced RoutineStep belongs to one of this goal's Routines, and
// FOCUS_TIME sums the `duration` of this goal's own completed PlannerBlocks directly. CUSTOM
// goals have no automatic source — `currentValue` is a plain user-supplied number, updated only
// via PATCH /goals/:id.
//
// Unlike Streak (Milestone 8), `currentValue` is a real, persisted column, not fully derived on
// every read: GET /goals and GET /goals/:id return whatever is currently stored (cheap — no
// source-table scan per goal in a list), and only GET /goals/:id/progress actually walks the
// source data and writes the refreshed value back, the same "explicit refresh, not implicit
// recompute-on-every-read" trade-off Milestone 8's own architecture note flags as the natural
// next step beyond pull-based evaluation. This keeps GET /goals cheap regardless of how many
// goals a user has, at the cost of `currentValue` only being as fresh as the last time
// GET /goals/:id/progress ran for that goal (mirroring the same "known, documented limitation"
// shape Milestone 8 already accepted for PlannerBlock-derived XP).
model Goal {
  id     String @id @default(uuid())
  userId String
  user   User   @relation(fields: [userId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)

  title       String
  description String?
  icon        String
  color       String
  // Free-text, like Habit.category — the milestone brief's Enums section defines GoalStatus/
  // GoalPriority/TargetType but not a category enum, so this follows Habit's own precedent rather
  // than docs/06-database-design.md's original GoalCategory enum sketch.
  category    String?
  priority    GoalPriority @default(MEDIUM)

  targetType   GoalTargetType
  targetValue  Int
  currentValue Int            @default(0)

  startDate  DateTime?  @db.Date
  targetDate DateTime?  @db.Date
  status     GoalStatus @default(NOT_STARTED)
  archived   Boolean    @default(false)

  createdAt DateTime  @default(now())
  updatedAt DateTime  @updatedAt
  // Soft delete, per docs/06-database-design.md's design principles — Goal is named there
  // explicitly, same as Task/Habit.
  deletedAt DateTime?

  milestones     GoalMilestone[]
  tasks          Task[]
  habits         Habit[]
  routines       Routine[]
  plannerBlocks  PlannerBlock[]
  journalEntries JournalEntry[]
  // Milestone 11: CalendarEvents that optionally reference this goal (e.g. a milestone-deadline
  // event) — see the comment on CalendarEvent. Not a new progress input: CalendarEvent doesn't
  // feed GoalTargetType/currentValue, the same "reference, not a progress source" treatment
  // JournalEntry.goalId already gets.
  calendarEvents CalendarEvent[]

  @@index([userId, status])
  @@index([userId, archived])
  @@map("goals")
}

// A Goal's own sub-checkpoints — structurally the same "steps belonging to a parent" shape as
// RoutineStep, so it follows the same conventions: no owner column of its own (reached only
// through `goal`, ownership enforced by joining `goal: { userId }`), hard delete (disposable,
// recreatable content, not named in docs/06-database-design.md's soft-delete list), and a manual
// `order` sort key. Unlike RoutineStep, milestone completion is entirely manual (`completed`/
// `completedAt`, toggled via PATCH /goals/milestones/:id) — it is deliberately NOT wired into
// Goal.currentValue: the milestone brief's "contribute automatically" business rules name only
// Task/Habit/Routine/PlannerBlock completions, not GoalMilestone completions, so a milestone is a
// user-tracked checkpoint alongside a goal's progress, not another progress input.
model GoalMilestone {
  id     String @id @default(uuid())
  goalId String
  goal   Goal   @relation(fields: [goalId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)

  title       String
  description String?
  dueDate     DateTime? @db.Date
  completed   Boolean   @default(false)
  completedAt DateTime?
  order       Int

  createdAt DateTime @default(now())
  updatedAt DateTime @updatedAt

  @@index([goalId, order])
  @@map("goal_milestones")
}

enum JournalType {
  MORNING
  EVENING
  FREEFORM
}

enum Mood {
  VERY_BAD
  BAD
  NEUTRAL
  GOOD
  EXCELLENT
}

enum Energy {
  VERY_LOW
  LOW
  NORMAL
  HIGH
  VERY_HIGH
}

// The user's personal timeline — a deliberately single, wide table covering all three JournalType
// variants (MORNING/EVENING/FREEFORM) with nullable type-specific columns, rather than three
// per-type tables or one `content` JSON blob. A morning/evening reflection and a freeform diary
// entry share the same identity/date/mood/energy/tags/attachments shape and the same list/search/
// history endpoints; splitting them into separate tables would mean three parallel CRUD paths and
// a `UNION` for any query spanning types (search, history, "related entries for this Goal"), for
// fields that are otherwise just... more nullable columns on one row. JSON was rejected for the
// same reason docs/06-database-design.md's note on Routine gives for choosing relational columns
// over `ScheduleTemplate.blocksJson`: `mood`/`energy`/`tags`/`goalId` need to be indexed and
// filtered on directly (GET /journal/search), which a JSON blob would make either impossible or a
// per-query JSON-path expression instead of a plain WHERE clause.
//
// Field groups, matching the milestone brief's own three sections:
// - Core (any type): title/content/mood/energy/productivity/tags/weather/location, plus the
//   optional goalId/plannerDayId cross-links.
// - Morning-only: intention/topPriorities/affirmation/visualization/expectedChallenges.
// - Evening-only: wentWell/wentWrong/lessons/gratitude/wins/plannerReflection/habitReflection/
//   goalReflection/tomorrowPlan.
// Every type-specific column is nullable and simply left unset by whichever type doesn't use it —
// there's no CHECK constraint tying a column to a specific `type` (the same trust-the-service-layer
// stance the rest of this schema takes for cross-field rules it can express more clearly in
// TypeScript than in SQL).
//
// `productivity` is a plain nullable Int (JournalEntryService validates 1-5), not a new enum: the
// milestone brief's Enums section defines only JournalType/Mood/Energy, so — matching the exact
// reasoning `docs/06-database-design.md`'s note on Goal gives for `category` staying free-text
// rather than getting a `GoalCategory` enum — an undefined enum isn't invented for it.
//
// Business rule ("one Morning Journal per day, one Evening Journal per day, unlimited Freeform")
// is enforced in JournalService (a friendly 409 via a `findFirst` check before create), not a
// database constraint: the rule is conditional on `type` (blocks MORNING/EVENING duplicates but not
// FREEFORM ones), which Postgres can only express as a *partial* unique index — a feature Prisma's
// schema DSL has no declarative syntax for without hand-written SQL in a migration file, which
// CLAUDE.md's "Never edit generated migration files" rule weighs against here. This is a documented,
// accepted limitation (a concurrent double-submit could in principle race past the service-layer
// check) — the same "known, documented trade-off" spirit as Milestone 8/9's own accepted gaps —
// rather than one worked around by hand-editing migration SQL. `@@index([userId, date, type])`
// still backs that check's query efficiently even without a uniqueness guarantee at the DB level.
//
// Soft delete (`deletedAt`), per the milestone brief's own "Journal is never deleted automatically"
// rule — the same principle docs/06-database-design.md already applies to Task/Habit/Goal.
//
// `goalId`/`plannerDayId` are optional, one-directional FKs (`onDelete: SetNull`, mirroring exactly
// how Task/Habit/Routine/PlannerBlock already point at Goal) — JournalModule validates ownership of
// both via a raw Prisma existence check (`assertGoalOwnership`/`assertPlannerDayOwnership`), not by
// injecting GoalsService/PlannerService, since neither of those modules imports JournalModule (no
// circularity risk either direction, unlike Goals' own fan-in), and every other module in this
// codebase already uses the raw-existence-check form for exactly this kind of optional
// cross-reference. Journal does not gain a new GoalTargetType (e.g. a hypothetical
// `JOURNAL_COUNT`) — the milestone brief doesn't ask for one, so a Goal's "related journal entries"
// (shown on Goal Detail) is a plain `GET /journal/search?goalId=` frontend query, not a progress
// input.
model JournalEntry {
  id     String @id @default(uuid())
  userId String
  user   User   @relation(fields: [userId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)

  // Date-only, like HabitLog.date/PlannerDay.date — the calendar day this entry belongs to, in
  // the user's own timezone (JournalService resolves "today" the same way PlannerService does,
  // reusing planner/utils/timezone.util.ts directly — see the comment on JournalService).
  date DateTime    @db.Date
  type JournalType

  title        String?
  content      String?
  mood         Mood?
  energy       Energy?
  // 1-5 self-rated scale (JournalEntryService validates the range) — see the comment above for
  // why this is a plain Int rather than a new enum.
  productivity Int?
  gratitude    String[] @default([])
  wins         String[] @default([])
  lessons      String?
  tomorrowPlan String?
  tags         String[] @default([])
  weather      String?
  location     String?

  // Morning-only fields — left null for EVENING/FREEFORM entries.
  intention          String?
  topPriorities      String[] @default([])
  affirmation        String?
  visualization      String?
  expectedChallenges String?

  // Evening-only fields — left null for MORNING/FREEFORM entries.
  wentWell          String?
  wentWrong         String?
  plannerReflection String?
  habitReflection   String?
  goalReflection    String?

  // Milestone 10: optional links back to a Goal/PlannerDay this entry reflects on — see the class
  // doc above for the ownership-validation and "no new GoalTargetType" rationale.
  goalId String?
  goal   Goal?   @relation(fields: [goalId], references: [id], onDelete: SetNull)

  plannerDayId String?
  plannerDay   PlannerDay? @relation(fields: [plannerDayId], references: [id], onDelete: SetNull)

  createdAt DateTime  @default(now())
  updatedAt DateTime  @updatedAt
  // Soft delete — the milestone brief's own "Journal is never deleted automatically" rule.
  deletedAt DateTime?

  attachments JournalAttachment[]

  // Milestone 11: CalendarEvents that optionally reference this entry. Per the milestone's own
  // business rule ("Journal entries remain read-only references"), a CalendarEvent may point at a
  // JournalEntry for display, but nothing about Journal itself changes — no calendar-awareness is
  // added to JournalService/JournalController.
  calendarEvents CalendarEvent[]

  @@index([userId, date])
  @@index([userId, date, type])
  @@index([userId, type])
  @@index([goalId])
  @@index([plannerDayId])
  @@map("journal_entries")
}

// Metadata for an already-hosted file (image, voice memo, etc.) attached to a journal entry — not
// binary storage. No object-storage provider (S3, Cloudinary, or even a local-disk multer setup)
// exists anywhere else in this codebase yet, and introducing one is exactly the kind of "add a
// dependency without justification" / scope-creep decision CLAUDE.md's "Things to Avoid" and this
// milestone's own "Only build the Journal system" instruction weigh against. `POST
// /journal/attachments` therefore registers metadata for a file the client already hosted
// elsewhere (`fileName`/`fileType`/`fileSize`/`url` are exactly the fields the milestone brief
// lists for this model) rather than accepting a multipart upload — the same reasoning that kept
// this milestone's frontend component list free of a dedicated "Attachment" component (see
// docs/07-folder-structure.md's note on features/journal/). Hard delete, like RoutineStep/
// GoalMilestone: disposable metadata reached only through its parent JournalEntry, not named in
// docs/06-database-design.md's soft-delete list.
model JournalAttachment {
  id        String       @id @default(uuid())
  journalId String
  journal   JournalEntry @relation(fields: [journalId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)

  fileName String
  fileType String
  fileSize Int
  url      String

  createdAt DateTime @default(now())

  @@index([journalId])
  @@map("journal_attachments")
}

// The reflection-prompt catalog — data-driven, following the exact same pattern
// docs/06-database-design.md's note on Achievement already established for Milestone 8's
// achievement catalog: rows are upserted from one TypeScript array
// (modules/journal/utils/journal-prompt-definitions.ts) at boot (JournalService.onModuleInit)
// rather than a separate `prisma db seed` step, so there's one source of truth instead of two that
// could drift. Not user-scoped — every user sees the same catalog, the same way Achievement's
// catalog isn't per-user (only the *unlock*, `UserAchievement`, is).
//
// `code` is one field beyond the milestone brief's own literal JournalPrompt field list — added
// for exactly the reason `Achievement.code` exists: `onModuleInit`'s upsert needs a stable,
// human-assigned identity to key on across restarts (a raw auto-generated `id` can't be
// hand-written into the definitions array ahead of the row existing).
model JournalPrompt {
  id          String      @id @default(uuid())
  code        String      @unique
  type        JournalType
  question    String
  placeholder String?
  order       Int
  active      Boolean     @default(true)
  createdAt   DateTime    @default(now())

  @@index([type, order])
  @@map("journal_prompts")
}

// Which system a Calendar is backed by. LOCAL is the only one this milestone actually syncs data
// for; GOOGLE/MICROSOFT/APPLE/ICAL rows can already be created (Calendar.provider accepts them
// today, per the "design as pluggable integrations" instruction) but their CalendarProvider
// adapter (see modules/calendar/providers/) always returns a FAILED CalendarSync with a "not yet
// implemented" errorMessage — see the comment on CalendarSync.
enum CalendarProvider {
  LOCAL
  GOOGLE
  MICROSOFT
  APPLE
  ICAL
}

// Whether a CalendarEvent originated locally (created directly, or via a link to a
// Task/Routine/PlannerBlock/Goal) or was pulled in from an external provider during a sync. Not
// meaningful yet for any provider besides LOCAL — kept as its own enum (not folded into
// CalendarProvider) because a future GOOGLE-provider Calendar could still contain a LOCAL-source
// event a user created directly inside LifeOS alongside SYNCED ones pulled from Google.
enum CalendarSource {
  LOCAL
  SYNCED
}

// A CalendarEvent's own lifecycle flag — ACTIVE for a normal event, DISABLED for one a user (or a
// future sync reconciliation) has turned off without deleting its history. Deliberately not named
// CONFIRMED/CANCELLED/TENTATIVE (the usual external-calendar vocabulary): this milestone doesn't
// model provider-side RSVP/confirmation states, only "is this event currently in effect."
enum CalendarStatus {
  ACTIVE
  DISABLED
}

// A user-owned calendar container — the same role Routine/Habit play as a "thing a user creates
// and configures," not a single implicit per-user calendar. LOCAL is the default and only fully
// functional provider this milestone builds; a Calendar row with `provider: GOOGLE` (etc.) can
// already be created so the frontend's Calendar Settings page and the provider architecture have
// something real to point at, but "connecting" one today only creates the row — no OAuth flow, no
// external API call exists anywhere in this codebase (see the class doc on ICalendarProvider).
// `timezone` is per-calendar (not read from User.timezone) because a user may deliberately keep a
// second calendar in a different zone (e.g. a shared/family calendar) — defaults to "UTC" like
// User.timezone does, and PlannerService/JournalService's own per-user timezone remains the
// source of truth for Planner/Journal "today" regardless of what a given Calendar's timezone is
// set to.
model Calendar {
  id     String @id @default(uuid())
  userId String
  user   User   @relation(fields: [userId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)

  name     String
  provider CalendarProvider @default(LOCAL)
  color    String
  timezone String           @default("UTC")
  enabled  Boolean          @default(true)

  createdAt DateTime @default(now())
  updatedAt DateTime @updatedAt

  events CalendarEvent[]
  syncs  CalendarSync[]

  @@index([userId, enabled])
  @@map("calendars")
}

// A single scheduled item on a Calendar. Ownership has no `userId` column of its own — like
// RoutineStep/PlannerBlock, it's only ever reached through its parent Calendar, ownership
// enforced by joining `calendar: { userId }` (see CalendarService).
//
// The four optional cross-links (`plannerBlockId`/`taskId`/`goalId`/`journalEntryId`) are the
// milestone's own "Planner blocks may create calendar events. Tasks may optionally create events.
// Goals may create milestone events. Journal entries remain read-only references." business
// rules, modeled identically to how Task/Habit/Routine/PlannerBlock already point at Goal
// (Milestone 9) and JournalEntry points at Goal/PlannerDay (Milestone 10): nullable FK,
// `onDelete: SetNull`, ownership validated in CalendarEventsService via a raw Prisma existence
// check rather than injecting TasksService/GoalsService/PlannerService/JournalService — the same
// "no circular-import risk, no need to depend on a whole sibling module for one id check" reason
// every prior cross-link already gives. `onDelete: SetNull` is what makes the milestone's
// "deleting linked objects should never delete calendar history automatically" rule true at the
// database level, not just in application code: deleting a Task/Goal/PlannerBlock/JournalEntry
// detaches this event from it but leaves the CalendarEvent row (and therefore the user's calendar
// history) intact.
//
// `externalId` is the id an external provider (Google/Microsoft/Apple/iCal) assigned to this
// event — null for every event today, since no sync path that could populate it exists yet (see
// the comment on Calendar). `source` distinguishes an event a user created directly
// (`LOCAL`, the only value ever written today) from one a future sync would pull in (`SYNCED`).
//
// No recurrence field/table (RRULE or otherwise) is modeled — the milestone brief's field list
// doesn't include one, and this milestone's own "Testing" section asks only for "recurring event
// preparation," not a working recurrence engine; see CalendarEventsService's recurrence-prep
// helper for the documented, tested subset (single-instance expansion) that stands in for it.
//
// Conflict detection (overlapping events within the same Calendar) is computed on read, not
// stored — the same "derived, not persisted" principle Routine/Habit/Goal already apply to their
// own completion percentages — reusing planner/utils/scheduler.util.ts's `hasOverlap`/`Interval`
// helpers directly rather than re-implementing overlap math a second time.
model CalendarEvent {
  id         String   @id @default(uuid())
  calendarId String
  calendar   Calendar @relation(fields: [calendarId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)

  plannerBlockId String?
  plannerBlock   PlannerBlock? @relation(fields: [plannerBlockId], references: [id], onDelete: SetNull)

  taskId String?
  task   Task?   @relation(fields: [taskId], references: [id], onDelete: SetNull)

  goalId String?
  goal   Goal?   @relation(fields: [goalId], references: [id], onDelete: SetNull)

  journalEntryId String?
  journalEntry   JournalEntry? @relation(fields: [journalEntryId], references: [id], onDelete: SetNull)

  externalId  String?
  title       String
  description String?
  startTime   DateTime
  endTime     DateTime
  allDay      Boolean        @default(false)
  location    String?
  source      CalendarSource @default(LOCAL)
  status      CalendarStatus @default(ACTIVE)

  createdAt DateTime @default(now())
  updatedAt DateTime @updatedAt

  @@index([calendarId, startTime])
  @@index([plannerBlockId])
  @@index([taskId])
  @@index([goalId])
  @@index([journalEntryId])
  @@map("calendar_events")
}

// An append-only log of sync attempts for one Calendar — one row per attempt, not a single
// "current state" row overwritten in place, so a calendar's sync history stays inspectable (e.g.
// a future Calendar Settings "sync history" panel) the same way UserAchievement's `unlockedAt`
// stays a durable fact rather than a mutable status flag. `status` is a plain String
// ("PENDING"/"SUCCESS"/"FAILED") rather than a new enum — the milestone's own Enums section names
// only CalendarProvider/CalendarSource/CalendarStatus, so (matching the exact precedent
// Goal.category and JournalEntry.productivity already set) an enum isn't invented for a field the
// brief didn't ask to be one; CalendarSyncService writes and validates one of "PENDING"/
// "SUCCESS"/"FAILED" on every row. `lastSync` is nullable because a FAILED attempt (every
// non-LOCAL provider today — see the comment on Calendar) has no successful completion instant to
// record; a SUCCESS row always sets it to the instant the sync finished.
model CalendarSync {
  id         String   @id @default(uuid())
  calendarId String
  calendar   Calendar @relation(fields: [calendarId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)

  lastSync     DateTime?
  status       String
  errorMessage String?

  createdAt DateTime @default(now())

  @@index([calendarId, createdAt])
  @@map("calendar_syncs")
}

// Which domain produced a Notification — one value per event source the milestone brief names
// (Tasks/Habits/Planner/Goals/Journal/Calendar/Streaks/Achievements), plus SYSTEM for anything
// that isn't a reaction to one specific feature's domain event (e.g. a future account-level
// notice). Achievements gets its own value distinct from STREAK — an unlocked achievement and a
// streak-consistency nudge read very differently to a user even though both originate from
// modules/streaks.
enum NotificationType {
  TASK
  HABIT
  PLANNER
  GOAL
  JOURNAL
  CALENDAR
  STREAK
  ACHIEVEMENT
  SYSTEM
}

enum NotificationPriority {
  LOW
  NORMAL
  HIGH
  CRITICAL
}

// A single field carries both "has this been delivered yet" and "what did the user do with it
// after delivery" — PENDING/QUEUED/SENT/FAILED are the delivery lifecycle, READ/DISMISSED are
// user-driven terminal states reached only from SENT. This matches the milestone brief's own
// literal enum exactly rather than splitting into two enums/columns; NotificationService is what
// enforces the lifecycle ordering (see its class doc).
enum NotificationStatus {
  PENDING
  QUEUED
  SENT
  FAILED
  READ
  DISMISSED
}

// A user's own delivered/read/dismissed reminders — created exclusively by
// NotificationSchedulerService reacting to a domain event (see the schema-level comment above),
// never written directly by a controller (per this milestone's own "do not deliver notifications
// immediately inside controllers" business rule). `payload` is a free-form JSON blob carrying
// whatever the originating event needs to deep-link back (e.g. `{ taskId }`, `{ habitId, date }`)
// without inventing a column per NotificationType — the same "don't index/query it directly, so
// don't force it into relational columns" reasoning CalendarSync.errorMessage/Goal.category
// already established for fields that don't need a WHERE clause of their own.
//
// Hard delete (DELETE /notifications/:id) — a notification is disposable, re-derivable-from-source
// content (the event that created it, or its source Task/Habit/etc., is still the record of truth),
// not the irreplaceable user-authored content docs/06-database-design.md's soft-delete principle
// protects, the same reasoning already applied to Routine/PlannerBlock/Calendar/CalendarEvent.
model Notification {
  id     String @id @default(uuid())
  userId String
  user   User   @relation(fields: [userId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)

  title    String
  message  String
  type     NotificationType
  priority NotificationPriority @default(NORMAL)
  status   NotificationStatus   @default(PENDING)

  // When this notification should become visible/delivered — "now" for most event reactions,
  // pushed later when quiet hours are in effect (see NotificationSchedulerService). Distinct from
  // `createdAt`, which is always the instant the row was written.
  scheduledFor DateTime
  deliveredAt  DateTime?
  readAt       DateTime?
  payload      Json?

  createdAt DateTime @default(now())
  updatedAt DateTime @updatedAt

  queue NotificationQueue?

  @@index([userId, status])
  @@index([userId, scheduledFor])
  @@index([userId, readAt])
  @@map("notifications")
}

// Per-user (1:1) notification settings — auto-created with defaults on first read (the same
// "find-or-create on first access" convention PlannerDay/HabitLog already establish for their own
// per-user rows), not provisioned at registration time, since nothing needs it before this
// milestone. `quietHoursStart`/`quietHoursEnd` follow RoutineStep.startTime/Habit.reminderTime's
// established "HH:mm" local-time-of-day string convention (nullable — quiet hours are off by
// default until a user sets both). `timezone` defaults to a copy of `User.timezone` at the moment
// this row is first created (see NotificationPreferenceService), the same "own column, seeded from
// the user's own timezone rather than recomputed from it on every read" shape `Calendar.timezone`
// already uses — a user could in principle want quiet hours evaluated in a different zone than
// their account's own, mirroring why Calendar keeps its own independent `timezone` column too.
model NotificationPreference {
  id     String @id @default(uuid())
  userId String @unique
  user   User   @relation(fields: [userId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)

  quietHoursStart String?
  quietHoursEnd   String?
  timezone        String  @default("UTC")

  enableTasks        Boolean @default(true)
  enableHabits       Boolean @default(true)
  enablePlanner      Boolean @default(true)
  enableGoals        Boolean @default(true)
  enableJournal      Boolean @default(true)
  enableCalendar     Boolean @default(true)
  enableStreaks      Boolean @default(true)
  enableAchievements Boolean @default(true)

  enableEmail Boolean @default(false)
  enablePush  Boolean @default(false)
  enableInApp Boolean @default(true)

  createdAt DateTime @default(now())
  updatedAt DateTime @updatedAt

  @@map("notification_preferences")
}

// One row per Notification, tracking its own delivery-attempt state — unlike CalendarSync's
// deliberately append-only "one row per attempt" log, this is a single mutable row per
// Notification because `attempts`/`nextAttempt`/`lastError`/`status` describe one ongoing retry
// process, not a history of independent attempts worth keeping separately (NotificationQueueService
// increments `attempts` and rewrites `nextAttempt`/`lastError`/`status` in place on every retry —
// see its class doc). `status` is a plain String ("PENDING"/"PROCESSING"/"SENT"/"FAILED"), not a
// new enum — the milestone's own Enums section lists only NotificationType/Priority/Status (all
// three already modeled on Notification itself), so, matching the exact precedent CalendarSync's
// own `status` column already set, one isn't invented here either. This is the seam a future
// BullMQ worker process (`main.worker.ts`, anticipated since docs/05-architecture.md but still
// unbuilt) drains — see NotificationQueueService.processDue for the callable-but-never-yet-
// scheduled method that stands in for that worker today, the same "documented, tested, not
// automatically invoked" shape Calendar's own recurrence.util.ts already established.
model NotificationQueue {
  id             String       @id @default(uuid())
  notificationId String       @unique
  notification   Notification @relation(fields: [notificationId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)

  attempts    Int       @default(0)
  nextAttempt DateTime?
  lastError   String?
  status      String    @default("PENDING")

  createdAt DateTime @default(now())
  updatedAt DateTime @updatedAt

  @@index([status, nextAttempt])
  @@map("notification_queues")
}

// Which domain an AiInsight analyzes. Six correspond 1:1 to the six read-only domains
// AiAnalysisService composes (Tasks/Habits feed HABITS+PRODUCTIVITY, Goals, Planner, Journal,
// Streaks); PRODUCTIVITY is the one cross-cutting type with no single owning module (it blends
// Task/Planner/Habit completion counts by day/weekday) — the same "not every type maps to one
// module" shape Notification's own SYSTEM value already has. SYSTEM is reserved for a future
// coach-level notice (e.g. onboarding, "no data yet") that isn't a per-domain analysis result;
// nothing in this milestone generates one yet.
enum InsightType {
  PRODUCTIVITY
  HABITS
  GOALS
  PLANNER
  JOURNAL
  STREAKS
  SYSTEM
}

// ACTIVE is the only state anything in this milestone writes — ARCHIVED/DISMISSED exist so
// GET /ai/insights can filter on them and a future milestone can add the obvious PATCH
// endpoint (the same "documented, not-yet-built seam" shape Calendar's recurrence.util.ts and
// Notification's CalendarEventStartingEvent already established) without a schema change.
enum InsightStatus {
  ACTIVE
  ARCHIVED
  DISMISSED
}

enum AiRole {
  USER
  ASSISTANT
  SYSTEM
}

// The durable output of one analysis run — one row per generated insight, never mutated by the
// analysis engine itself (only a future dismiss/archive endpoint would ever update `status`, per
// the comment on InsightStatus). `sourceData` is the metrics AiAnalysisService computed and handed
// to the provider (e.g. `{ completionRateThisWeek, completionRateLastWeek, deltaPercent }` for a
// PRODUCTIVITY insight) — stored verbatim so the Dashboard's Productivity Trend/Risk Alert widgets
// can read structured numbers directly instead of parsing `content`'s prose, and so a human can
// audit exactly what data a given insight was based on. Not encrypted/sensitive the way
// JournalEntry.content is — these are read-only derived summaries of a user's own already-stored
// productivity data, not free-form personal reflection.
//
// `confidence` is a plain 0.0-1.0 float the provider self-reports (MockAiProvider derives it from
// how much source data backed the computation — e.g. a 2-week trend is more confident than a
// 3-day one), not a stored/enforced accuracy metric.
//
// `generatedAt` and `createdAt` are deliberately two separate columns even though MockAiProvider
// always writes the same instant to both today: `createdAt` is "when this row was written" (the
// convention every model in this schema follows), while `generatedAt` is "when the underlying
// analysis was actually performed" — a future async provider (a real OpenAI/Anthropic/Google
// integration queued as a background job) could create the row when the request is accepted but
// only set `generatedAt` once the provider actually responds, the same reason `Notification` keeps
// `scheduledFor` distinct from `createdAt`.
//
// No `deletedAt` — insights are disposable, re-derivable analysis output (the source Task/Habit/
// Goal/etc. rows remain the record of truth), not the irreplaceable user-authored content
// docs/06-database-design.md's soft-delete principle protects, the same reasoning already applied
// to Notification/Calendar/PlannerBlock.
model AiInsight {
  id     String @id @default(uuid())
  userId String
  user   User   @relation(fields: [userId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)

  type       InsightType
  title      String
  summary    String
  content    String
  confidence Float
  status     InsightStatus @default(ACTIVE)
  sourceData Json?

  generatedAt DateTime
  expiresAt   DateTime?

  createdAt DateTime @default(now())

  @@index([userId, status])
  @@index([userId, type])
  @@index([userId, generatedAt])
  @@map("ai_insights")
}

// A user's own AI Chat thread — `title` is nullable and left unset until AiConversationService
// derives one from the first user message (truncated), the same "auto-derived, not required at
// creation" shape as leaving it blank being a valid state. Hard delete would be the natural choice
// (disposable, like Notification) but no delete endpoint is built in this milestone at all — see
// docs/API.md's AI Coach section — so this is a documented gap, not a modeling decision either way.
model AiConversation {
  id     String @id @default(uuid())
  userId String
  user   User   @relation(fields: [userId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)

  title String?

  createdAt DateTime @default(now())
  updatedAt DateTime @updatedAt

  messages AiMessage[]

  @@index([userId, updatedAt])
  @@map("ai_conversations")
}

// One row per chat turn. No `userId` of its own — like RoutineStep/GoalMilestone, it's only ever
// reached through its parent AiConversation, ownership enforced by joining `conversation: { userId
// }`. `role` follows the USER/ASSISTANT/SYSTEM shape every LLM chat-completion API already uses
// (a future OpenAI/Anthropic/Google provider maps directly onto it); this milestone's MockAiProvider
// only ever produces ASSISTANT messages, but SYSTEM is modeled now so a future system-prompt-as-a
// stored-message design doesn't require a migration.
model AiMessage {
  id             String         @id @default(uuid())
  conversationId String
  conversation   AiConversation @relation(fields: [conversationId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)

  role    AiRole
  content String

  createdAt DateTime @default(now())

  @@index([conversationId, createdAt])
  @@map("ai_messages")
}
